	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Light above, that turned flame-ish right quick, didn't it ...<br />
<br />
We're a tight-knit guild, 100+ members. Most of our guildies I know or have personally spoken to, though we've gotten practically a herd of new ones in the last two weeks that I'm still working with. Do I know their birthdays? Some of them, yep, most of them, nope. When I send new guildies tells about visiting our forum and such, I do make it a point to introduce myself, RL name, and tell them I'm from North Carolina. A lot of us are on a first-name basis. <br />
<br />
Do we use LFG when /raiding? Yep, all the time. In fact, it's getting to be an unspoken requirement to attend an SOTA raid ... no LFG tag = no invite. Why? As someone who organizes A LOT of raids, LFG is a great tool. Seeing those capital letters next to someone's name makes it REAL easy to group up and get organized.  <br />
<br />
Is it impersonal, as Kurth was trying to say? Sure, you could construe it as such. 'Course then again, one can construe nearly anything in nearly any way one wishes.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><font size="1"><b><font color="navy">Mystic <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=856112" style="color:navy">Tordail</a> Farstryder</b><br />
Officer, Shaman Class Leader<br />
<a href="http://eqhalcyons.guildwizard.com/index.aspx" style="color:navy">Halcyon</a> of <a href="http://www.rathetravelagency.com/phpbb" style="color:navy">The Rathe</a></font></font></div>
	
	
