	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />see what im trying to get at ?<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Not really lol. Youre ranting about big guilds using LFG?<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />why the hell would you go LFG on a raid?<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Its an efficient way to find out who still needs a group. I know a lot of my guildies pretty well. 10-20 of us are on teamspeak (voice chat) during raids. I know what countries / states a lot are from, and on voice chat its obvious whos from other countries. I can tell you what the last piece of gear a lot of them got or go even further back than that. But how is any of that going to help me know if they need a group???<br />
<br />
Even with 35-45 people I cant imagine how your raid spontaneously materializes without some communication. Or how people could just show up at a raid, not say anything, and get invited. Some people use /gu lfg and that works sometimes. Its not that practical to have 60 people spamming gu at the start of every raid imo. Or realistic for someone showing up after the raid is going to expect an invite instantly every time from a simple /gu lfg There are all kinds of reasons that they might have to hang out a few mins before getting invited, might as well put up an lfg tag. Imo at least.<br />
<br />
I've never tried to limit who can see me when Im lfg. Might take a look at it now. Tho getting lfg tells is not a huge gripe of mine. For a while now Ive been using the filters to block seeing LFG people from other guilds that I dont like from showing up in searches when Im building groups. Kinda funny when I was on vacation building a group that didnt have those filters in place. I was like, how the hell did this guy get into my group! lol.</p>
	
	
	
