	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The group-maker does a /list 1 or whatever number that channel is. There - he has a list of all people attending the raid.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>This presupposes that everyone in the raid joins the channel. Maybe my old guild was just really bad at this, but getting people to do stuff like this (or /consent monks/rogues/necros for dragging after wipes, or asking for buffs, or a bunch of other things), you always end up with several people who are AFK or doing other stuff, or chatting, or whatever, and they don't get into the channel.<br />
<br />
Setting up groups with LFG just always seemed to be most efficient. It's a no-brainer for what to do...don't have a group? Turn on LFG! The raid leader picks group leaders (usually clerics), each of those forms as well balanced a group as they can from the LFGs. If you need specific requirements (say, 5 rangers and a bard), those people tend to already know it and form up their groups accordingly. Making raid groups isn't exactly rocket science. It is pretty rare that 5-6 XP-style groups formed up into a raid won't be able to handle everything perfectly.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
