</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Hail,<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />/em pulls out rant stick...<br />
why the hell would you go LFG on a raid?<br />
is this a closed guild raid ? or an open naggy/vow type raid ?<br />
if so, doesn't your guild know you enough to invite you by name and not class/lvl ? i see this alot on drinal with uber guilds, i think its kinda gimpy.<br />
my guild isn't that uber but we can do saryn,tt, and a few other pop raid targets and such, but it always buggs me when i wanna exp grind and need a clr lfg, and i see 9+ clerics lfg in VEX THAL...<br />
my guild has somewhere near 35-45 people on during raid nights, and yet we still seem to invite/know all of our members, is the uber guild heirarchy about being "nameless_leet_player_01" ??<hr size="1" /></blockquote>The /lfg tool is useful for both closed and opened raids as well as just normal grouping, where  I use it to exclude members of a certain guild from my window using the filter.  Sorry you feel its gimpy, but you are entitled to your opinion.  Since I'm not uber, I'll just ignore the 'nameless_leet_player_01' comment.<br />
<br />
I've marked myself "LFA Miragul only" and I still get tells asking for me to come to BoT (ick <img src="images/smilies/mad.gif" border="0" alt="" title="mad" smilieid="9" /> ).  Some people use the tools, some use /who all 60 65 shaman.  The latter people won't see my /lfg message because they never used the tools.  That's life.<br />
<br />
When I'm forming a group for LDoN myself, I use /who lfg AND the tools.  I don't ask people in the EP or time to group, and people in questionable zones (like BoT, where people could either be gathering for a Tower/Agnarr raid or actually sitting in the safe room really LFG) I generally ask if they are raiding or if they might like to join my adventure group.<br />
<br />
I don't get upset when people don't use the tools &amp; filters, although the multiple group requests can be annoying at times.  If you use the tools it will reduce but not eliminate this.  I also think there are some people who think they are using the filters but use /lfg on instead of clicking the button so their filter message maybe getting lost.  /shrug. <img src="images/smilies/cool.gif" border="0" alt="" title="cool" smilieid="7" /> <br />
<br />
I'm a member of a very small guild (~20 active mains, another ~20 in alts) that is allied with 2 other small guilds.  We typically use /lfg flags to snag the ungrouped, even if we only have 2-3 groups total raiding out of the combination of 3 guilds.  It is a handy tool, efficient and convenient.  Some of our members are not outspoken, and would likely go through an hour or two of raiding ungrouped without complaint.  The LFG tag over their head is sort of obvious though, and it also makes group reorganization for specific purposes much easier.  The person who is moving from one group to another will put /lfg on when they are ready for the re-invite.  This reduces the /invite button spam for the second group leader (since sometimes the person moving has to leave the group and the raid, etc).<br />
<br />
Weissblau, thanks for sharing your tip.  Though I don't see it as very practical for my own situation, I could see it as handy for others.<br />
<br />
Take care,</p>
	
	
	
