<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>weissblau</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Heyokah<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: May 2001<br />
	Location: Halas
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Gee, I never read the followups, lol.<br />
<br />
Yes, I know what class/level everyone in our guild is, with the exception of perhaps a few that have joined in the past couple of weeks.  However, we always go LFG upon arriving at a raid site.   The raid leader gives a raid invite to individuals, usually healers, as raid group leaders, and those individuals are responsible for forming their own BALANCED groups out of the LFG population.  If someone is already grouped, they won't be LFG.  If we're really concerned about group balance the RL may make a few adjustments before engagement by moving individuals around, but most of the time this method produces workable groups for almost zero effort on the part of the raid leader.  <br />
<br />
When we are COH'ing from one location to another during the raid,  we drop raid and go LFG for COH invite.  On the other end, group leaders ask for raid invite to the new raid and then re-invite their groups.  The COH teams can do /who LFG to get the list of people waiting for COH.<br />
<br />
If your guild doesn't use LFG on raids, fine, but there ARE uses for them in large guilds, even when the people do know each other.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=529003">Twoflower Tourist</a> - <a href="http://www.unionofpower.org">Union of Power</a><br />
68 Heyokah<br />
Rodcet Nife</div>
	
	
